  <subsection permid="Jqz">
    <title>Imaginary Numbers</title>
    <p permid="tMc">
      Let's look at how to simplify a square root that has a negative radicand.
      Remember that <m>\sqrt{16}=4</m> because <m>4^2=16</m>.
      So what could <m>\sqrt{-16}</m> be equal to?
      There is no real number that we can square to get <m>-16</m>,
      because when you square a real number,
      the result is either positive or <m>0</m>.
      You might think about <m>4</m> and <m>-4</m>, but:
      <me permid="KKn">
        4^2=16\text{ and }(-4)^2=16
      </me>
      so neither of those could be <m>\sqrt{-16}</m>.
      To handle this situation,
      mathematicians separate a factor of
      <m>\sqrt{-1}</m> and represent it with the letter <m>i</m>,
      which stands for <term>imaginary unit</term>.
    </p>

    <definition permid="uhB" xml:id="definition-imaginary-number">
      <title>Imaginary Numbers</title>
      <idx><h>imaginary unit</h></idx>
      <idx><h>imaginary numbers</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="ksq">
          The <term>imaginary unit</term>, <m>i</m>,
          is defined by <m>i=\sqrt{-1}</m>.
          The <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_number">imaginary unit</url><fn>
          <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_number">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary<underscore />number</url>
          </fn> satisfies the equation <m>i^2=-1</m>.
          A real number times <m>i</m>,
          such as <m>4i</m>, is called an
          <term>imaginary number</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p permid="ZTl">
      Now we can simplify square roots with negative radicands like <m>\sqrt{-16}</m>.
      <md permid="qRw">
        <mrow>\sqrt{-16}\amp=\sqrt{-1\cdot16}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{16}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=i\cdot4</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=4i</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p permid="Gau">
      Imaginary numbers are widely used in electrical engineering, physics,
      computer science and other fields.
      Let's look some more examples.
    </p>

    <example permid="aoK">
      <statement>
        <p permid="wGI">
          Simplify <m>\sqrt{-2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="WoL">
        <p permid="zBo">
          <md permid="WYF">
            <mrow>\sqrt{-2}\amp=\sqrt{-1\cdot2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=i\sqrt{2}</mrow>
          </md>
          We write the <m>i</m> first because it's difficult to tell the difference between
          <m>\sqrt{2}i</m> and <m>\sqrt{2i}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="GvT">
      <statement>
        <p permid="cNR">
          Simplify <m>\sqrt{-72}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="CvU">
        <p permid="fIx">
          <md permid="DfO">
            <mrow>\sqrt{-72}\amp=\sqrt{-1\cdot36\cdot2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{36}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6i\sqrt{2}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="pxI">
    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations with Imaginary Solutions</title>
    <example permid="mDc">
      <statement>
        <p permid="IVa">
          Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>x^2+49=0</m>,
          where <m>x</m> is an imaginary number.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="iDd">
        <p permid="LPG">
          There is no <m>x</m> term so we will use the square root method.
          <md permid="jmX">
            <mrow>x^2+49\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2\amp=-49</mrow>
          </md>
          <md permid="Pug">
            <mrow>x\amp=-\sqrt{-49} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=\sqrt{-49}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{49} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{49}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=-7i\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=7i</mrow>
          </md>
          The solution set is <m>\{-7i,7i\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="SKl">
      <statement>
        <p permid="pcj">
          Solve for <m>p</m> in <m>p^2+75=0</m>,
          where <m>p</m> is an imaginary number.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="OKm">
        <p permid="rWP">
          There is no <m>p</m> term so we will use the square root method.
          <md permid="vBp">
            <mrow>p^2+75\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>p^2\amp=-75</mrow>
          </md>
          <md permid="bIy">
            <mrow>p\amp=-\sqrt{-75} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp p\amp=\sqrt{-75}</mrow>
            <mrow>p\amp=-\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{25}\cdot\sqrt{3} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp p\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{25}\cdot\sqrt{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>p\amp=-5i\sqrt{3}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp p\amp=5i\sqrt{3}</mrow>
          </md>
          The solution set is <m>\left\{-5i\sqrt{3},5i\sqrt{3}\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection permid="VER">
    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations with Complex Solutions</title>
    <p permid="mhD">
      A <term>complex number</term> is a combination of a real number and an imaginary number,
      like <m>3+2i</m> or <m>-4-8i</m>.
    </p>

    <definition permid="yRu" xml:id="definition-complex-number">
      <title>Complex Number</title>
      <idx><h>complex number</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="Qzz">
          A <term>complex number</term> is a number that can be expressed in the form <m>a + bi</m>,
          where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers and <m>i</m> is the imaginary unit.
          In this expression, <m>a</m> is the
          <term>real part</term> and <m>b</m>
          (not <m>bi</m>)
          is the <term>imaginary part</term>
          of the <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number">complex number</url><fn>
          <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex<underscore />number</url>
          </fn>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
         <!-- todo: figure out if fn can be inserted into a term.
         <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number">complex number</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex<underscore />number</url></fn> -->
    <p permid="SoM">
      Here are some examples of equations that have complex solutions.
    </p>

    <example permid="eYD">
      <statement>
        <p permid="Vjs">
          Solve for <m>m</m> in <m>(m-1)^2+18=0</m>,
          where <m>m</m> is a complex number.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="uRv">
        <p permid="YdY">
          This equation has a squared expression so we will use the square root method.
          <md permid="HPH">
            <mrow>(m-1)^2+18\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>(m-1)^2\amp=-18</mrow>
          </md>
          <md permid="nWQ">
            <mrow>m-1\amp=-\sqrt{-18} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp m-1\amp=\sqrt{-18}</mrow>
            <mrow>m-1\amp=-\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp m-1\amp=\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>m-1\amp=-3i\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp m-1\amp=3i\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>m\amp=1-3i\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp m\amp=1+3i\sqrt{2}</mrow>
          </md>
          The solution set is <m>\left\{1-3i\sqrt{2}, 1+3i\sqrt{2}\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="LfM" xml:id="example-solve-quadratic-complex-solution">
      <statement>
        <p permid="BqB">
          Solve for <m>y</m> in <m>y^2-4y+13=0</m>,
          where <m>y</m> is a complex number.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="aYE">
        <p permid="Elh">
          Note that there is a <m>y</m> term,
          but the left side does not factor.
          We will use the quadratic formula.
          We identify that <m>a=1</m>,
          <m>b=-4</m> and <m>c=13</m> and substitute them into the quadratic formula.
          <md permid="UdZ">
            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(-4)\pm\sqrt{(-4)^2-4(1)(13)}}{2(1)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{4\pm\sqrt{16-52}}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{4\pm\sqrt{-36}}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{4\pm\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{36}}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{4\pm6i}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2\pm 3i</mrow>
          </md>
          The solution set is <m>\{2- 3i, 2+ 3i\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p permid="yvV">
      Note that in <xref ref="example-solve-quadratic-complex-solution">Example</xref>,
      the expressions <m>2+3i</m> and <m>2-3i</m> are fully simplified.
      In the same way that the terms <m>2</m> and <m>3x</m> cannot be combined,
      the terms <m>2</m> and <m>3i</m> can not be combined.
    </p>

    <remark>
      <p permid="eDe">
        Each complex solution can be checked,
        just as every real solution can be checked.
        For example,
        to check the solution of <m>2+3i</m> from <xref ref="example-solve-quadratic-complex-solution">Example</xref>,
        we would replace <m>y</m> with <m>2+3i</m> and check that the two sides of the equation are equal.
        In doing so, we will need to use the fact that <m>i^2=-1</m>.
        This check is shown here:
        <md permid="Ali">
          <mrow>y^2-4y+13\amp=0</mrow>
          <mrow>(\substitute{2+3i})^2-4(\substitute{2+3i})+13\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>(2^2+2(3i)+2(3i)+(3i)^2)-4\cdot 2 -4\cdot (3i) +13 \amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>4+6i+6i+9i^2-8-12i+13 \amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>4+9(-1)-8+13 \amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>4-9-8+13 \amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
          <mrow>0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

